bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Office of the Provost at The George Washington University was created in 1969 as the Provost and Vice President for Academic Affairs. The position was the chief administrative officer under the President, working with, admissions, academics, and affirmative action programs on campus. Oswald C. Colclough, who was twice acting President of GW, served as Provost from 1961-64. Harold F. Bright served in the post from 1969-74, and was succeeded by William D. Johnson, who served from 1984-89, when the position was abolished to streamline administration.

In 2003 the position was reinstituted, with the charge to oversee the offices of communication and governmental, international, and corporate affairs, as well as handling daily administrative duties during the President's absence. Dr. John L. "Skip" Williams, Dean of the School of Medicine and Health Sciences was the first person to hold the newly revitalized post. The Provost reports to the President.

The Office of Associate Provost was created in 1984, with Marianne R. Phelps as head. This position was responsible for the coordination of all equal employment and affirmative action programs at the university. In 1985 the office published the report of the Commission for the Year 2000, which examined the academic future of the University.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include correspondence, by-laws, affirmative action plans, memos, meeting minutes, agendas, and reports. They range in date from 1973-2011, and were transferred to the University Archives by the University Provost. Note: Not all series are processed. Ask staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into eight series: Office files; Commission on Equal Opportunity; Office files; Division of Extension; Commission for the Year 2000; Department planning reports; Office files; and Accession 2014.023.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of office files relating to Ben Franklin University, Omicron Delta Kappa, Provost Office budget, admissions, registrar, university historian, School of Education, College of General Studies, National Law Center, School of Engineering, University Library, athletics, student activities, residence halls, Marvin Center, University Club, and chronological files. The materials range in date from 1965-88.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Commission for the Year 2000 was charged by President Lloyd Elliott with studying the mission and programs of The George Washington University and with recommending new program directions or emphases to place the University among the leading universities of the world over the next fifteen years. Associate Provost Marianne R. Phelps Chaired the Commission. John G. Boswell, Chair of the Department of Education and Professor of Education, L. Thompson Bowles, Dean of the Medical Center for Academic Affairs and Professor of Surgery, Edward A. Caress Associate Dean of the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences and Professor of Chemistry, William R. Johnson, Chair of the Department of History and Associate Professor of History, William H. Marlow, Professor of Operations Research, Robert E. Park, Professor of Law, Susan J. Tolchin, Professor of Public Administration, Harry E. Yeide, Chair of the Department of Religion and Professor of Religion, Roderick S. French, Vice President for Academic Affairs, ex-officio, William D. Johnson, Provost, ex-officio, rounded out the membership of the committee.
This series consists of correspondence, minutes, agendas, reports. The materials range in date from 1984-85.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains legal documents and documents related to the Welling professorship. The Welling Professorship brings internationally distinguished scholars to GW to deliver lectures and interact with students and faculty in the Business school. The professorship is named after James Clark Welling, who served as the university's president in the late 19th century.
